<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Temptation of the Ring<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.45)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11682'>Paul "Hetfool" Twomey</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11682&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 18, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Can You Protect Me from Yourself?<br>
<br>
Exhaust Aragorn or Add 2 burdens? The choice is one for your opponent, but what which would you prefer? For best results use this card is best used in an Exhaustive/Burden deck, but none the less it can be a nasty in disguise. It has the potential to get rid of the annoying effects of his bow for at least one turn if needs be, or alternatively give Frodo even more of a headache. So to what kind of deck should you add this to?<br>
<br>
The most obvious connection for this card is Isengard Orcs, given their exhaustive capabilities; it makes Tower of Orthanc very useful and can be a lot easier to achieve than the regroup exhaust abilities of the Overseer and Berserker. It makes sense then in these cases that the Free-Peoples player would rather take the burdens, so why not make that choice more difficult. The Relams version of Otsea and Blade Tip make for a mean combination, even the Twilight Witch-King can make it very painful and if you add The Ring Draws Them then either way you&#8217;ll be getting more shadow. You could get the jump by using Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul and if 6 companions of 5 burdens are about then you can kill of Aragorn if your opponent takes the exhaustive approach. You can also bet that Aragorn will be made an archer in almost all decks with his bow, so if your playing this combination you can add Relentless charge, which can once again potentially wipe Aragorn out. Black Breath can also up the stakes a little, played on Aragorn early, given condition removal will come into play, he may remain Exhausted longer giving extra opportunities to use the previously mentioned combinations to wipe him out.<br>
<br>
You can pair it up with Sauron too for an even more powerful punch. Why not use Enduring Evil, Desperate Defence of the Ring and Thin and Stretched to try and force your opponent to exhaust Aragorn. When this happens you need only Hate him once and he goes the way of the do-do. If he chooses to add burdens instead, chances are you will overwhelm Aragorn anyway with Enduring Evil. If you&#8217;re lucky enough too to be up against a 5 or more companion deck then Caradhras has not forgiven us will obviously discard the exhausted Aragorn. If the burdens are added it can allow Traitor&#8217;s Voice to take effect or make the effects of Worry or Verily I Come felt even more. The Eye of Sauron will also assist in this case too to improve the draw of your own deck considering it may suffer in attempting some of these combinations.<br>
<br>
This seems like a lot to do for once card, but in perspective it really makes existing strategies more viable if your opponent is playing Aragorn. I would only ever add 2 copies of this card at most but I would add it, if not just for the surprise value.<br>
<br>
Too Great And Terrible<br>
<br>
Wound Gandalf twice or discard two Gandalf cards from hand? Given the annoying number of Gandalf cards around you would think this is a blessing in disguise. Fireworks, Staff Asunder, Servant of the Secret fire just to name a few are all extremely useful and powerful in a number of decks featuring Gandalf, so is this a new and lethal way of combating it.<br>
<br>
Gandalf has the potential to have a vitality of 6, so two wounds may not seem so bad, but straight away you remove the possible effects of either of the staffs and cards like Staff Asunder if you get the two wounds. You can also effectively kill Gandalf in one foul with three copies of this card and one Nazgul in play, as the shadow cost is zero. Chances are no player will be able to resist adding the wounds to Gandalf unless they are playing a Trust, Gandalf signet deck. However the chances of exhausting Gandalf to use Hate in a similar combination to the one discussed for Can You Protect Me From Yourself? is not very high. You need to have extra cards up your sleeve to make Too Great and Terrible useful. <br>
<br>
Gates of the Dead City can be a real pain with this card, given you can have four copies out at once and Gandalf if at a vitality of 6 is most likely to exert from this card. However the Gandalf Shadow removal is probably too strong to use this consistently. Having said that any strategy that you use to get wounds on companions is greatly affected by Gandalf&#8217;s shadow removal.<br>
<br>
You could use the Isengard/Nazgul decks to try and make it more viable to kill of Gandalf with this card. You can play a few Damage+1 Uruks, one Nazgul  and Saruman&#8217;s Snows and then pull out Too Great and Terrible. If he adds the wounds then you can play News of Mordor to ensure everyone is damage+1 and Gandalf will probably take even a few more wounds. Chances are however this combination is too hard to generate at the right time. <br>
<br>
This leaves us with only one option, to play multiple copies of this card in one play to try our best to wound Gandalf up as much as possible. This can cause hand clogs and a few other dramas however so at best it will be a lottery.<br>
<br>
In the end this card appears useful, but it hard to get going especially considering your opponent will most likely choose wounds instead. It can be triumphant in a Trust deck and if you get the right playing circumstances it can kill Gandalf. The question is however, is this lottery worth it? <br>
<br>
I would add this card to any condition heavy deck to try your best to get rid of those pesky Gandalf cards that rock the boat. Potentially it is as much of a failure as it is the best card in your deck.<br>
<br>
Such A Little Thing<br>
<br>
Wound Boromir three times or discard 2 Free-Peoples possessions? Does there need to be much more said about this card? <br>
<br>
Boromir can often be the bane of a Moria Swarm deck with his nasty Blade of Gondor, so can other possessions on other characters like Frying Pan, Long-Knives of Legolas, Sting and so on. This card finally gives a Moria Swarm the chance to get rid of a few of those possessions if not getting rid of Boromir.<br>
<br>
Unless your opponent is playing The Saga of Elendil, which is common you will kill him if not for the other option. This makes the chances of getting rid of Free-Peoples possessions extremely high and in a swarm deck you should be rejoicing. Even if they are using Saga and exhaust Boromir you can pair it up with Frenzy to assign a Moria Orc to Boromir in an attempt to destroy him.<br>
<br>
You can use this in an Isengard/Moria combination that uses Hate and Anger. This will allow you to pair it up with Can You Protect me From Yourself? to make those new Gondor decks suffer big time and bring all the exhaustive stuff discussed earlier into play more easily. In this combination you can use Troubles Mountains to generate even more shadow. Overall however, Discarding two Free-Peoples possessions can have far greater implications in many combinations and I would recommend on copy of this card at least to at least every single Moria deck on the playing scene. <br>
<br>
If you combine this with a Nazgul deck and play a couple Cantea&#8217;s you can potentially rip all companions of their useful weapons creating a situation of hopelessness for your opponent. This card also has the potential to upset the Horn leaving some Ally decks unable to handle a swarm.<br>
<br>
In the end this card has many implications far greater than what I have written and should be considered in many different deck types. This card makes the addition of Boromir to the oppositions Fellowship a move more detrimental than valuable.<br>
<br>
Why Shouldn&#8217;t I Keep It<br>
<br>
Discard Bilbo or discard 2 Free-Peoples Possessions? Bilbo is not so much of a pain in decks these days and in the end he is only truly useful in competitive decks for recycling of Shire events. The leaves this card useful against mainly Hobbit decks that utilise stealth or other such cards. <br>
<br>
It can be useful as a singular addition to a Sauron deck just to stop the recycling of Stealth events for the later sites. Generally the Free-Peoples player will also be using Gandalf or Boromir, or perhaps even Aragorn so if you want to be sneaky you can add any of the previously mentioned cards in some combination to take down an arrogant friend of yours who has won for too long with his Hobbit stealth deck.<br>
<br>
In the end however this card has far less use than any of the others. Discarding Bilbo may not hurt so much as losing a number of Shire conditions like Countryside, Talent, Elbereth, or There and Back Again. <br>
<br>
Keep this card for those days you think you will need to combat such strategies or you going into a friendly competition, in a competitive deck this is mainly a waste of space.<br>
<br>
Terrible As The Dawn<br>
<br>
Wound Galadriel three times or discard two elves? Potentially the bane for any number of the new Elf Ally decks that will generally feature Galadriel in some way. You can negate the Mirror, you can prevent her new ability of replacing sites, you can also ruin the healing capabilities of those darn site 6 Elf Allies. <br>
<br>
Basically at least one copy of this card is a must inclusion for any Sauron deck because it can effectively wipe out the Elven Strategy. It is a pretty simply choice for your oppoent and if you play Tower Assasin can effectively wipe out the Ally strategy in one foul swoop. Not much more can be said for its value in terms of that really.<br>
You can team it up with Moria by using Malice to again take out those archery decks, or even add Such A Little Thing to make the Horn and Boromir useless too un such a strategy. <br>
<br>
In the end however I would keep at least one copy in a Sauron or Sauron/??? Combination deck to prevent things like the Mirror and Site 6 allies from having any kind of fun.<br>
<br>
